Для того чтобы можно было искать музыкантов по городам и избежать путаницы, вам необходимо сделать следующее:

1. Измените способ ввода города с текстового поля на выпадающий список, чтобы пользователи могли выбирать из доступных городов.

2. Создайте новый массив `predefinedCities`, который будет содержать список городов, из которого пользователи могут выбирать при регистрации. 

3. Добавьте функцию поиска музыкантов по городам, редактируя существующую функцию `search`.

4. Выведите на страницу поиска выбор города среди заранее определенных в массиве.

Исходя из текущего кода, приведу ниже изменения, которые потребуются.

1. Создайте массив `predefinedCities` в файле `app.js` ниже массива `predefinedGenres`:

```javascript
const predefinedCities = ['New York', 'Los Angeles', 'Chicago', 'Houston', 'San Francisco'];
```

2. Замените текстовое поле для ввода города в файле `register.ejs` на выпадающий список:

```html
<label for="location">Location</label>
<select id="location" name="location" required>
  <option value="">Select a city</option>
  <% predefinedCities.forEach(city => { %>
    <option value="<%= city %>"><%= city %></option>
  <% }) %>
</select>
```

3. Обновите функцию `search` в файле `app.js`, чтобы добавить поиск по городам. В этом примере я добавляю дополнительный параметр `city` и обновляю фильтр и сортировку:

```javascript
function search(query = '', role = '', city = '') {
  // ... existing code ...

  if (query || role || city) {
    const lowerQuery = query.toLowerCase();
    // ... existing code ...
    return nameScore + genreScore > 0 && (role === '' || musician.role === role) && (city === '' || musician.location === city);
  }).sort((a, b) => {
    // ... exising code ...
  });
  }

  return results;
}
```

4. Добавьте поле выбора города на страницу поиска в файле `search.ejs`:

```html
<label for="location">Search by city:</label>
<select id="location" name="location">
  <option value="">All cities</option>
  <% predefinedCities.forEach(city => { %>
    <option <%if (city == location) { %>selected<% } %> value="<%= city %>"><%= city %></option>
  <% }) %>
</select>
```

5. В файле `app.js` добавьте строку в маршруте `'/search'` для выделения `location` из URL-параметров запроса:

```javascript
const location = req.query.location || '';
```

6. Выведите переменную `location` в качестве дополнительного параметра в функцию `search` в маршруте `'/search'`:

```javascript
musicians = search(query, role, location);
```

Теперь, когда пользователь зарегистрируется, он должен выбирать город из списка заранее определенных городов, и поиск можно будет производить как по имени и жанру, так и по роли и городу.

I cannot directly create a Unity project for you here, but I can provide you with detailed instructions on how to create a simple 2D top-down game with ML Agents in Unity.

Prerequisites:
1. Make sure you have Unity installed (preferably the latest version).
2. Make sure you have the ML Agents package installed and imported into your project. You can find the package in Unity Package Manager or download it from the official GitHub repository: [ML-Agents](https://github.com/Unity-Technologies/ml-agents)

Step 1: Create a new Unity 2D project
1. Open Unity Hub and create a new 2D project.

Step 2: Set up the environment and game objects
1. In the Hierarchy, right-click and create an empty GameObject. Name it "Environment".
2. Right-click "Environment" and create a new square 2D sprite. Name it "Player" and set its scale to (0.5, 0.5, 1). This sprite will represent the circle character.
3. Right-click "Environment" again and create a new square 2D sprite. Name it "Food" and set its scale to (0.3, 0.3, 1). This sprite will represent the food circles.

Step 3: Add components to Player and Food
1. Select the "Player" object in the Hierarchy, then click the "Add Component" button on the Inspector. Add a "Circle Collider 2D" component.
2. Click the "Add Component" button again and select "New Script". Name it "PlayerController" and click "Create and Add".
3. Select "Food" in the Hierarchy, and click "Add Component". Search for "Circle Collider 2D" and set that up as well.

Step 4: Create an Academy and Agent
1. Right-click the Hierarchy and create an empty GameObject. Name it "CircleAgentAcademy".
2. Click "Add Component" and select "New Script". Name it "CircleAgentAcademy" and click "Create and Add".

3. In the "CircleAgentAcademy" script, you need to inherit from "Unity.MLAgents.Academy" instead of "MonoBehaviour". Then, you don't need to define any further properties or methods for now.

```csharp
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;
using Unity.MLAgents;

public class CircleAgentAcademy : Academy
{

}
```

4. Select the "Player" object in the Hierarchy and click "Add Component". Search for "Agent" and add the "Agent" component to the Player object.
5. Click "Add Component" again and select "New Script". Name it "CircleAgent" and click "Create and Add".

6. In the "CircleAgent" script, you need to inherit from "Unity.MLAgents.Agent" instead of "MonoBehaviour". Implement the required methods and properties for controlling the character's movements, collecting rewards, and resetting the environment.

Step 5: Train the Agent
1. Follow the official [ML-Agents Documentation](https://github.com/Unity-Technologies/ml-agents/blob/master/docs/Installation.md) to set up the Python environment required to train the agent.
2. Look into ML-Agents documentation's [Basic Guide](https://github.com/Unity-Technologies/ml-agents/blob/master/docs/Basic-Guide.md) to learn how to train your agent using the provided training configurations.

After you have a trained model, you can use it with your Unity project and switch to keyboard controls as needed.
Here's an example PlayerController script that would allow keyboard control with WASD anytime you don't have a neural network loaded:

```csharp
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;

public class PlayerController : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float moveSpeed = 5.0f;

    void Update()
    {
        float horizontal = Input.GetAxis("Horizontal");
        float vertical = Input.GetAxis("Vertical");

        transform.position += new Vector3(horizontal * moveSpeed * Time.deltaTime, vertical * moveSpeed * Time.deltaTime, 0);
    }
}
```

In your Academy script, you can use the `Academy.Instance.IsCommunicatorOn` property to check if a neural network is being used. If the agent isn't communicating with the Python process, then you can enable the PlayerController script:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;
using Unity.MLAgents;

public class CircleAgentAcademy : Academy
{
    public GameObject player;

    void Start()
    {
        if (!IsCommunicatorOn)
        {
            player.GetComponent<PlayerController>().enabled = true;
        }
    }
}
```

Remember to assign the "Player" object to the "player" property of the "CircleAgentAcademy" script in the Unity Inspector.

And that's it! You should now be able to train your agent using ML-Agents and switch to keyboard control when a neural network is not being used.

