The reason the provided code doesn't handle overshooting is because it doesn't consider the time it takes to decelerate the body when it nears its target. You just limit the body's speed to `maxSpeed`, but when it is very close to the target position, it is still too fast and can overshoot it.

To fix this, you can add a deceleration factor that reduces the body's speed based on the distance remaining to the target position. And also, utilize delta time in calculations.

For better handling of high velocities, using a smoothed approach can be helpful. Here's one way to modify the code to prevent the overshoot:

```java
public static Vector2 velocityToPosition(Body body, Vector2 targetPosition, float maxSpeed, float deltaTime) {
    Vector2 position = body.getPosition();
    Vector2 velocity = body.getLinearVelocity();

    // point in target direction
    Vector2 targetDirection = targetPosition.cpy().sub(position);

    float distance = targetDirection.len();

    // Calculate a deceleration factor based on the distance to the target
    float decelerationFactor = Math.min(distance * 0.1f, 1.0f); // This factor can be adjusted to experiment with different deceleration rates

    // Calculate velocity needed to reach the target in the time of one update
    Vector2 desiredVelocity = targetDirection.scl(maxSpeed * decelerationFactor / distance);

    // Smoothly interpolate between the current velocity and the desired velocity using delta time
    velocity.lerp(desiredVelocity, deltaTime * 60); // Multiply deltaTime with 60 because your STEP_FREQUENCY seems to be 60

    return velocity;
}
```

Now, instead of immediately setting the velocity to a certain value, we smoothly interpolate between the current velocity and desired velocity using delta time. Additionally, we added a deceleration factor that reduces the body's speed when its distance to the target position is short, making it less likely to overshoot the target. The `0.1f` in the deceleration factor calculation can be adjusted to experiment with different deceleration rates.

You can call this method with an additional deltaTime parameter in this way:

```java
